article.description:
Jason Terry swished a
3-pointer with 18 seconds left as the Mavericks rallied from a
12-point deficit for a 101-98 win over the SuperSonics on Friday
night.
article.headline: Mavericks rally to upend Sonics in Seattle
article.linkText: Mavericks rally to upend Sonics in Seattle
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Since joining the Dallas Mavericks, Jason Terry has really enjoyed coming home. Terry made a critical shot in the closing moments back in Seattle for the second straight season. This time, he swished a 3-pointer with 18 seconds left as the Mavericks rallied from a 12-point deficit for a 101-98 win over the SuperSonics on Friday night. Last season, Terry made a 3-pointer with 8 seconds left in a Dallas victory. On Friday, Terry made two 3-pointers in the final two minutes and helped the Mavs win for the 10th time in the last 12 games. "I'm just thriving in the moment of getting the ball in late game situations and wanting to take the shot," Terry said. "You have to, and that's what want to do." Dallas improved to 4-3 in the second game of a back-to-back after beating Sacramento on Thursday night. Terry was quiet until the fourth quarter, when he scored 12 points and helped Dallas rally from an 87-75 deficit with less than 8 minutes left. He finished with 19 points. The Mavs went 2-1 on their brief swing up the West Coast, but coach Avery Johnson was still smarting about Tuesday's loss to the Los Angeles Lakers, when Kobe Bryant scored 62 points in three quarters. "We don't feel good about what happened to us in Los Angeles and it's going to serve as motivation for us," Johnson said. A night after scoring a season-high 37, Dirk Nowitzki followed up with 34 points and 13 rebounds. Josh Howard added 20 points, 14 in the second half. Seattle lost for the sixth time in its last nine games and has dropped five of its last six home games. Vladimir Radmanovic led the Sonics with 20 off the bench. Ray Allen added 19, but shot just 8-of-21 and Rashard Lewis scored 16 points and had 12 rebounds. "Christmas came early for Dallas. We gave them one," Seattle coach Bob Weiss said. "Right now we're pressing. Guys are making turnovers we don't need to make, we're making fouls we don't need to make and we're missing shots we could be hitting." Dallas went scoreless for the first 4:32 of the fourth quarter, getting its first points on a pair of free throws from Terry. Nowitzki added a pair of free throws, before making the Mavs' first field goal of the quarter with 6:31 left pulling them within 87-81. Nowitzki then hit a jumper as Dallas rattled off 13 of the next 15 points, trimming Seattle's lead to 89-88. Radmanovic then made an aggressive drive and scored, but two free throws from Nowitzki and Terry's 3-pointer gave Dallas a 93-91 lead with 2 minutes left. Allen's jumper gave Seattle one final lead, but Terry found Nowitzki under the basket for a dunk, and a 96-95 lead with 51 seconds left. After a Seattle miss, Terry made a 3-pointer from the top of the key and added a pair of free throws in the final seconds. "He had a stretch there were he wasn't playing particularly well. But we just keep reminding him of who he is and he hit some big shots for us," Johnson said. Dallas outscored Seattle 31-19 at the free throw line and was 14 of 16 in the fourth quarter. Ronald Murray added 15 off the bench for Seattle. The Sonics outrebounded Dallas 47-37 and had 21 second-chance points, but shot just 5-of-20 on 3-pointers. "We realize the present situation we're in and just have to build from there," Allen said. Dallas' Jerry Stackhouse made his season debut, checking in with 3:34 left in the first quarter. Stackhouse missed the first 26 games because of swelling in his right knee, caused by a deep bruise in Dallas' first preseason game. His first basket came on a reverse layup with 10:40 left in the second quarter. He finished with eight points and played 16 minutes. Seattle received a scare late in the first half, when Luke Ridnour was injured. Ridnour collided with Stackhouse and crumpled to the floor moments later. He remained on the court for a minute, but got up and walked off the court under his own power. The team said Ridnour had a chest contusion and he started the second half.

Game notes
Terry spent part of the pregame pulling together 80 tickets for friends and family. ... Marquis Daniels missed his second straight, and fourth in the last five games, with a neck strain. ... Dallas G Devon Harris missed part of the second half with an upset stomach. He returned briefly in the fourth quarter.
